Commentary.Commentary: We are back for Bangladesh's batting! Pakistan fielders have taken the field. Mahmudul Hasan Joy and Shadman Islam walk out to bat. Shaheen Afridi will start with the ball.

Pakistan started their innings with another fifty run-stand by their openers. But soon both got out in quick succession. It was the experienced duo of Azhar Ali and Babar Azam that bailed them out and stitched together a century partnership. The rain played spoilsport as almost the whole of Day 2 and the entire Day 3 was washed out. On Day 4, both the overnight batters departed and then it was the pair of Fawad Alam and Mohammad Rizwan that took them to a formidable total before they decided to declare eventually. It looks like there is only one team that can win from hereon and it is Pakistan. Can their bowlers get early wickets and make this game more interesting? We shall find out.

Bangladesh bowlers were good on the first morning of this Test match. As Taijul Islam got both the openers in that session. But even though the conditions were quite helpful for bowlers, they failed to get breakthroughs and allowed partnerships to build after that. On the morning of Day 4, seamers bowled well and managed to take two early wickets but again gave away loose deliveries at regular intervals and are now on the back foot in this Test match.

An innings that lasted for more than three days, all thanks to the rain! So Pakistan have declared! They have 300 on the board and will be now looking to dismiss Bangladesh as early as possible. Still, a draw looks more likely but you never know anything can happen as the conditions are bowling-friendly out there.

Ebadot Hossain first got the wicket of Azhar Ali with a short ball and then Khaled Ahmed took his first Test wicket as he trapped Babar Azam in front of his stumps. The good work continued as Bangladesh bowlers kept the pressure on with their nagging lines and lengths. Overall a decent session for Bangladesh and they will be looking to get a few more wickets in the post-Lunch session

Hello and a warm welcome to the coverage of Day 3 of the second Test between Bangladesh and Pakistan. There was more focus on weather than cricket on Day 2 as rain dominated the proceedings and made sure that both Pakistan and Bangladesh fans end up being equally disappointed at the end of the day. If we talk about cricket, there was a brief session of play in which 38 balls were bowled in which both Azhar Ali and Babar Azam scored runs freely and added 27 runs to the overnight score. Azhar Ali notched up his fifty while Babar Azam is moving towards his first Test century as a Pakistan captain. The conditions were overcast and Mominul Haque trusted his seam bowlers. But both the bowlers were completely ineffective and gave away too many freebies to Pakistan batters before the rain came back to end their misery. The forecast for Day 3 is not that promising, to be honest, and let us hope that rain stays away.
... Day 3, Session 1 ...

Right then. That is all we have from this rain-marred day of Test cricket. Not much cricket on this day and plenty of rain. Day 3 is scheduled to begin at 9:30 am local (3:30 am GMT). The forecast is not too great, to be honest with you. But we can hope. Do join us for the same!

Only 38 balls were bowled on Day 2 but clearly that brief period was dominated by Pakistan. 27 runs were scored as Azhar Ali notched up his fifty on the way. Bangladesh seamers were all over the park as they bowled way too many loose deliveries and displayed no potential to take any advantage of overhead conditions. So far, the match has been dominated by Pakistan and if the rain stays away on Day 3 we might see some more free-flowing batting by Pakistan batters.
So the official news is out! The day has been called off.

Hello and a very warm welcome to the coverage of Day 2 of the second Test between Bangladesh and Pakistan. We had 57 overs of play on Day 1 and it is Pakistan who will be relatively happier with their performance. The day started with Pakistan openers putting a solid 59-run stand but Bangladesh spinners soon got into the act and Taijul Islam dismissed both the openers in quick succession. After a shared first session, the experienced duo of Azhar Ali and Babar Azam steadied the ship and guided them to 161 without any further damage. There was no play possible after Tea though as the light faded away. There is enough turn on offer for Bangladesh bowlers and the first session will be key here as the batting will only get tougher from here on. An interesting day of Test cricket coming up.
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

That is all from Day 1. Pakistan would be disappointed as the two batters were looking in good touch out in the middle but nature had different plays. We will see you on 5th December for Day 2 though. The first ball will be bowled at 9:30 am local (3:30 am GMT). So mark your alarms accordingly. Cheers!

Earlier in the day, after winning the toss, Babar Azam decided to bat first. Pakistan openers started from where they left in the first Test and notched up another fifty-run partnership as they dominated the first hour of the day. But in the second hour of the play, Bangladesh spinners got into the act and Taijul Islam sent the two in-form openers back to the hut. The spinners were brilliant before the Lunch and it looked like they will get more wickets in the next session. But the experienced duo of Azhar Ali and Babar Azam weathered the storm and have managed to stitch together a partnership of 91 runs. There was a short rain break in the middle session but the final break to the proceedings of the day was put by the fading light and there was no play possible after Tea

The bails come off! That is stumps on Day 1. The umpires have decided that play cannot continue further on Day 1. The match will start at 9:30 am local on Day 2 instead of 10 am. But, we are likely to have rain interruptions for the next two days.

Bangladesh have their perennial problems to deal with coming into this second Test. Their top order faltered again in both the innings of the Test match and gave away any advantage gained by them at the end of the first innings. They failed to deal with the swing and pace of Pakistan bowlers and with Saif Hassan ruled out they will be hoping that the new opening partnership that takes the field will give them a better start. The good news for them is certainly the return of Shakib Al Hasan as the star all-rounder will strengthen both their batting and bowling in this game. If their batting can put up decent scores on the board, then their bowling has enough strength to take 20 wickets in a Test match, especially if the wicket assists the spinners more. Can Bangladesh make a comeback and avoid a series loss at home? Or will Pakistan hand a whitewash to Bangla Tigers at their home turf? We shall find out. Stay tuned.

The first Test turned out to be a test of grit and determination of the Pakistan team. They were put under pressure throughout the course of the game but every time they found a way to come out on the top. Their openers were fantastic and dished out a century partnership in both the innings of the Test. The bowling was dominated by their seamers as Hasan Ali and Shaheen Afridi bagged a five-wicket haul in the first and second innings respectively. But it was not a perfect game for them by any stretch of the imagination. The Pakistan middle order faltered after a century stand by their openers in the first innings and coming into this game, the likes of Babar Azam, Fawad Alam and Azhar Ali will be looking to make more contributions. Their spinners too were not that effective and with Dhaka's pitch known to assist spin a little more, the spinners will be eyeing more impact in this game. Pakistan have a well-settled unit and will be looking to seal the series 2-0. Can Bangladesh stop them? We shall find out.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 1 of the second Test between Bangladesh and Pakistan. The action now shifts to Dhaka and Bangladesh will hope that the change in venue also brings a change in fortune for them. It was Pakistan who came out victorious in the first Test but the game was quite evenly poised almost till Lunch on Day 4. But in Test cricket, it is about playing consistent cricket over the course of five days and that is where Pakistan inched ahead and in the end, registered a comfortable victory. Can Bangladesh bring more discipline to their game and manage to level this series at their national capital. Or will Pakistan register a crucial away series win in this second cycle of the World Test Championship? Either way, some quality Test cricket awaits us.

We are back for the action again! Pakistan players are out there in the middle. The opening batters for Bangladesh, Mahmudul Hasan Joy and Shadman Islam are there in the middle too. Shaheen Afridi to start with the ball for Pakistan.

So Pakistan now need 10 wickets and have almost a full day in front of them now. The match now looks heavily in the favour of Pakistan and Bangladesh will have to come out with different tactics if they have to survive till the end of the day.

Shaheen Afridi set the tone with a brilliant first over on Day 4. After that, the spinners Sajid Khan and Nauman Ali bowling in tandem and created pressure from both ends and Sajid Khan eventually took his first five-wicket haul to restrict Bangladesh to 76/7 at the end of Day 4. Sajid Khan took the wicket of Taijul Islam in his very first over on Day 5 and then Shaheen Afridi got rid of Khaled Ahmed in the very next over. Sajid Khan took the final wicket of Shakib Al Hasan and finished with eight wickets in the end. Pakistan have enforced the follow-on with a lead of 213 runs. They are in with a real chance now and Pakistan will be hoping that they can continue their good work from the first innings.

Bangladesh's innings started on the worst possible note as Mahmudul Hasan Joy, the debutant departed for a duck in his first innings. Soon his opening partner followed him and wickets continued to crumble as none of the batters showed the application to spend some time in the middle. They came out with bizarre tactics of going for their shots on every possible opportunity and paid the price in return. This match needed some very dreadful cricket from one team to take us to a result and Bangladesh have done exactly that on Day 4. It is now upto Pakistan to build on that and get early wickets on Day 5 to put Bangladesh under more pressure on this final day. Pakistan seamers were not allowed to bowl yesterday after the first over because of fading light, but they will be ready to explode this morning and that makes the task of playing out this day even tougher for Bangladesh. Hello and a warm welcome to the coverage of Day 5 of the second Test between Bangladesh and Pakistan. After two days of almost no cricket, the action on Day 4 finally provided cricket fans with some exciting cricket. The first session was delayed due to the wet outfield, but once the game started it was Pakistan who dominated the proceedings and have now taken the game to a situation where they are in with a real chance of victory on Day 5. Day 4 started with Bangladesh seamers bowling in good areas and getting rid of overnight Pakistan batters very early in the day. But things went downhill after that as first Fawad Alam and Mohammad Rizwan stitched together a century stand as Pakistan declared for 300. Then, Pakistan spinners and especially Sajid Khan who bagged six wickets completely dismantled Bangladesh batting as they are left tottering at 76/7 after the end of day 4 with 25 more needed to avoid follow on. Can Bangla Tigers salvage a draw in this Test match? Or will Pakistan hand Bangladesh a humiliating defeat in their own backyard? An interesting day of Test cricket coming up.

Right then! This brings us to an end of an exciting Day 4 of this Test match after we were greeted by only rain in the previous two days. The forecast for Day 5 looks promising and we can expect another cracking day of Test cricket from these two teams. Do join us at 9:30 am local time (3:30 am GMT). Till then, goodbye and cheers!

Earlier in the day, after a late start to the first session, Bangladesh bowlers struck early to send back both the overnight batters back to the pavilion. But another brilliant century stand between Fawad Alam and Mohammad Rizwan took Pakistan to 300 before they eventually declared. The bowlers came in with some aggressive attitude and picked three Bangladesh wickets for almost nothing and that set the tone for a brilliant post-Tea session.

Bangladesh batters came out like they were chasing 201 in 20 overs here. They tried to hit every ball that was possible for them and ended up losing wickets at regular intervals. Mushfiqur Rahim was first to go early in the session but the shot-making continued even though wickets were falling regularly. It took bad light to stop them from self-exploding and in the end, they have lost a total of seven wickets and it looks too tough for Bangladesh from hereon.

Another session that was pocketed by Pakistan. The spin bowlers bowling in tandem were brilliant and kept the pressure on as Bangladesh batters came out with bizarre tactics. Sajid Khan got rid of Mushfiqur Rahim early in the session and got another wicket of Liton Das as Bangladesh batters looked in some sort of a strange hurry. The off-spinner then went onto take six wickets as Bangladesh batters struggled to show any application in the middle. Pakistan have taken seven wickets in no time and despite the rain and bad light, they are in with a chance to win this Test match.

Drinks! What a bizarre piece of batting by Bangladesh here! Okay, scratch that. The umpires have decided to end the day's play as the light is not enough. Pakistan would be mighty pleased with their show on Day 4 and a result looks likely now!

Right then, this brings us to the end of this fascinating Test series between Bangladesh and Pakistan. Both the Test matches were closely contested but in the end, we have to say that Pakistan was a better team. They have clinched the series 2-0 and have also bagged 24 WTC points on the way. We will be back with more such thrilling action and till then, goodbye and cheers!

Babar Azam, the skipper of Pakistan, says that he enjoyed his bowling and he is glad that he got his first international wicket. Adds that their openers gave them a good start and their bowlers did a terrific job. Says that even though they lost a couple of days due to rain, they wanted to dominate the game and he is very happy with the win. Credits all the groundsmen by saying that they did a good job of covering the whole ground at all times.

The Bangladesh skipper, Mominul Haque, says that they had opportunity to get better in the second innings. He adds that middle order played well but they need to work on their top order. Tells that there were some positives for them and hopefully these players can continue their form in New Zealand.

Abid Ali is the Player of the Series. He says that the pitch was not easy to bat and it was turning. He adds that they wanted to play with a positive approach and everyone backed each other. He mentions that his domestic form helped him to perform in this series.

Sajid Khan is the Player of the Match for his brilliant bowling performance. He says that his captain and team management backed him and he is very happy. Tells that it is a team effort and everyone has contributed equally for the win.

Earlier in this game, Pakistan batters played pretty well on the tough Dhaka pitch as four batters notched up their fifty. The rain played spoilsport for almost two whole days and that made Pakistan declare for 300. Then, it was time for Pakistan bowlers to unleash their full potential and they did that in style as they bundled out Bangladesh for 87 runs. Bangladesh followed on and lost four wickets quickly but there was some sensible batting after that but eventually, it is Pakistan who have clinched a very unlikely victory here.

For the most part of the session, Pakistan bowlers didn't look like they will get four wickets in this session. But just when all hopes were fading, Babar Azam brought himself on and broke the partnership by dismissing Mehidy Hasan. Sajid Khan took his 10-wicket haul in the next over and soon followed it up with the 11th wicket. The last wicket took some time after that but Sajid Khan again came to the party and trapped Taijul Islam in front to hand Pakistan crucial 12 WTC points from this Test.

The final session saw Shakib Al Hasan and Mehidy Hasan batting sensibly but just when it looked like Bangladesh will salvage a draw here, Babar Azam displayed his magic and took the wicket of Mehidy Hasan. The well set Shakib Al Hasan also departed in the next over and in no time they were nine down with Khaled Ahmed perishing on duck. Taijul Islam and Ebadot Hossain played out some overs but Sajid struck again and ended with 12 wickets in this Test match, to hand Pakistan a very special win.

What a Test match this has been! When two days were almost completely washed off, very few believed that this Test will get a result. But Pakistan believed and played some quality cricket and in the end, with less than half an hour remaining in this Test match, they have clinched a victory here.

Pakistan bowlers found it difficult to get breakthroughs in this session as Bangladesh batters finally displayed some application out there in the middle. Sajid Khan eventually got the wicket of Liton Das and there was enough turn in the pitch to keep them interested. But some resilient batting by Bangladesh after that did not allow Pakistan to make further inroads. But just at the stroke of the Tea, the run-out of Rahim has brought them back into this game now. Can Pakistan take the remaining four wickets to clinch 12 WTC points from this Test match? All questions will be finally answered in the last session of this Test match coming our way. This is Test cricket at its best. Do join us for some intriguing action in the final session of this Test match at 3:00 pm Local time ( 9:00 am GMT).

The session started with Liton Das and Rahim building up a nice partnership much to the frustration of Pakistan bowlers. But just when things were getting calmer for Bangla Tigers, Liton Das perished at the score of 45 while trying to pull a half-tracker. The experienced duo of Rahim and Shakib Al Hasan then got together and stitched together a nice partnership as they combined caution with aggression beautifully. But just at the stroke of Tea, the brain-fade moment from two batters sent Rahim back to the pavilion as he was run-out. Bangladesh still trail by 66 runs. Will the run-out cost them this Test match? We shall find out.

OUT! RUN OUT! Oh, dear! Mushfiqur Rahim gets out just at the stroke of Tea and he would be absolutely gutted with himself! This is a huge moment in the context of this game and it is surely a body blow for Bangladesh. This was needless from Rahim and it could cost Bangladesh in the end. It was a flatter ball, on middle. Shakib Al Hasan tucks it to mid-wicket and goes for a run. Abdullah Shafique at mid-wicket collects the ball cleanly and throws it to the keeper Mohammad Rizwan who whips the bails off. Mushfiqur Rahim puts in a dive but his bat bounced off the ground and wasn't grounded before Rizwan took the bails off. The TV umpire has a good look at it and gives it out in the end. Mushfiqur Rahim walks back in anger and that will be Tea on Day 5.
They have gone upstairs for a Run-Out appeal! Mushfiqur Rahim has dived at the batter's end and can that save him? No, he has been given out! Big blow for Bangladesh.

The same story continued for Bangladesh as they were bundled out for just 87 in the first innings. The poor show continued when they were made to follow-on as the top order crumbled against the pace and swing of two Pakistan seamers. Since then, Rahim and Liton Das got together and have stitched together a decent partnership to take them to Lunch without further damage. They are still 141 runs behind and have to bat two sessions out from hereon to salvage a draw here. Do join us for the second session which will begin at 12.40 pm Local (6.40 am GMT).

Another dominating performance by Pakistan bowlers. They came out in the morning with three more wickets needed to bundle out Bangladesh in the first innings and they did that pretty quickly as Sajid Khan finished with eight wickets under the belt and Shaheen Afridi took one wicket. They came back in the second innings as Bangladesh were made to follow-on and seamers got into the act immediately as they picked two wickets apiece to restrict Bangladesh to 25/4 in the ninth over. They have picked seven wickets in the first session and are just six wickets away from getting a famous win here.
